From 3eefe9fce92f83630cd0c516dfd6d7607467106c Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Will Nelson <will.nelson@discordapp.com>
Date: Thu, 30 Apr 2026 19:01:23 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 2/3] kotlin/highlights.scm: rewrite chain-method patterns to
 be O(n)
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The four (call_expression …) patterns that match chained method calls
were O(n^2) on deeply chained input (~3 s on 16 KB), because the
QueryCursor descended into the left-recursive navigation_expression
at every nested call_expression. Rewrite to be genuinely O(n):

1. The chain-method-name pattern
       (call_expression (navigation_expression
           (navigation_suffix (simple_identifier) @function))))
   becomes a non-descending scope capture
       (call_expression . (navigation_expression) @callable.chain)
   which captures the whole receiver-chain navigation_expression as a
   single span and lets the highlight pipeline retag any
   @property capture whose end byte coincides with this scope's end
   byte (= the last navigation_suffix in the chain = the actual call
   target) into @function. Same final captures, O(n) work.

2. The three regex-call patterns (toRegex/Regex/Regex.fromLiteral)
   gain leading-` . ` first-child anchors at every nesting level.
   For chain-shaped input the anchored slot is occupied by a
   navigation_expression (not a string_literal or simple_identifier),
   so the structural match short-circuits at every call_expression
   and these rules are O(n). They keep their @string.regex captures
   intact.

Verified end-to-end: depth=8000 chain (32 KB input) drops from
12.3 s to 48 ms (256x), and capture distribution on a realistic
kotlin file is byte-identical after the pipeline post-process pass.

The companion arborium-rt change in src/highlight.rs implements the
post-process upgrade. Without that pipeline change this commit
removes the @function highlight on chained method names; with it,
@function highlighting is fully preserved.
---
 .../kotlin/def/queries/highlights.scm         | 48 +++++++++++++++----
 1 file changed, 40 insertions(+), 8 deletions(-)

diff --git a/langs/group-bark/kotlin/def/queries/highlights.scm b/langs/group-bark/kotlin/def/queries/highlights.scm
index a0df0a2..c040faf 100644
--- a/langs/group-bark/kotlin/def/queries/highlights.scm
+++ b/langs/group-bark/kotlin/def/queries/highlights.scm
@@ -135,10 +135,24 @@
 	. (simple_identifier) @function)
 
 ; object.function() or object.property.function()
+;
+; Capture the receiver chain as a scope, not the function-name identifier
+; itself. The runtime then upgrades any (navigation_suffix (simple_identifier))
+; @property capture whose end byte coincides with this scope's end byte
+; (i.e. is the last suffix in the chain — the actual call target) into
+; @function.
+;
+; Why: matching the function name directly with
+;   (call_expression (navigation_expression (navigation_suffix
+;     (simple_identifier) @function)))
+; is O(n^2) on deeply-chained calls because the QueryCursor descends into
+; the left-recursive navigation_expression at every nested call_expression
+; (~3 s on a 16 KB chain). Capturing the navigation_expression node as a
+; whole with no inner pattern keeps the matcher at O(1) per call_expression
+; — the leading `.` anchor pins it to the first-child slot — so the entire
+; rule is O(n).
 (call_expression
-	(navigation_expression
-		(navigation_suffix
-			(simple_identifier) @function) . ))
+	. (navigation_expression) @callable.chain)
 
 (call_expression
 	. (simple_identifier) @function.builtin
@@ -218,16 +232,28 @@
 
 ; There are 3 ways to define a regex
 ;    - "[abc]?".toRegex()
+;
+; Both anchors are necessary: the outer `.` pins the navigation_expression
+; to call_expression's first-child slot; the inner `.` pins the
+; string_literal to the navigation_expression's first-child slot. Together
+; they short-circuit the structural match at every call_expression in a
+; deeply-chained input (where the first child is a navigation_expression,
+; not a string_literal), keeping this rule O(n).
 (call_expression
-	(navigation_expression
-		((string_literal) @string.regex)
+	. (navigation_expression
+		. ((string_literal) @string.regex)
 		(navigation_suffix
 			((simple_identifier) @_function
 			(#eq? @_function "toRegex")))))
 
 ;    - Regex("[abc]?")
+;
+; Leading `.` anchor — for chain-shaped input the first child of
+; call_expression is a navigation_expression (not a simple_identifier),
+; so the structural match short-circuits at every call_expression and
+; this rule is O(n).
 (call_expression
-	((simple_identifier) @_function
+	. ((simple_identifier) @_function
 	(#eq? @_function "Regex"))
 	(call_suffix
 		(value_arguments
@@ -235,9 +261,15 @@
 				(string_literal) @string.regex))))
 
 ;   - Regex.fromLiteral("[abc]?")
+;
+; Both anchors: outer `.` pins navigation_expression to first-child of
+; call_expression; inner `.` pins simple_identifier to first-child of
+; navigation_expression. For chain-shaped input the inner first-child is
+; another navigation_expression, so the structural match short-circuits
+; and this rule is O(n).
 (call_expression
-	(navigation_expression
-		((simple_identifier) @_class
+	. (navigation_expression
+		. ((simple_identifier) @_class
 		(#eq? @_class "Regex"))
 		(navigation_suffix
 			((simple_identifier) @_function
